  "response": "The lack of civil sense in India is a complex issue with multiple contributing factors:\n\n1. Historical and social reasons:\n- Colonial legacy\n- Socioeconomic disparities\n- Deeply ingrained hierarchical social structures\n- Overcrowding and resource scarcity\n\n2. Educational factors:\n- Limited focus on civic education\n- Inadequate emphasis on personal responsibility\n- Low awareness about public etiquette\n- Weak implementation of civic rules\n\n3. Cultural aspects:\n- Individualistic mindset\n- Lack of collective social responsibility\n- Limited respect for public spaces\n- Weak enforcement of social norms\n\n4. Systemic issues:\n- Ineffective governance\n- Poor infrastructure\n- Weak legal consequences for civic violations\n- Corruption\n\n5. Psychological factors:\n- Sense of anonymity in large populations\n- Reduced accountability\n- Limited empathy towards others\n- Survival-oriented mindset\n\n6. Economic pressures:\n- Daily struggle for basic necessities\n- High stress levels\n- Limited time for social considerations\n\nAddressing these issues requires a multi-dimensional approach involving education, policy changes, social awareness, and individual commitment to improving civic behavior.\n\nNote: These are generalized observations and do not apply uniformly across India's diverse population.",
